UID:kMB3BFYlaPEgmEvGwTE1j
SUMMARY:Biochemical and Structural Characterization of Viral Multimeric Com
	plexes Associated with Replication
DTSTAMP:20260616T175127Z
DTSTART:20260616T200000Z
DESCRIPTION:&#160\;  Speaker: Yifei Yang  Doctoral Candidate  Thesis Defens
	e  Department: BioSciences-Biochemistry and Cell Biology  Location: BioSci
	ence Research Collaborative BRC 875  RNA-dependent RNA polymerase (RdRp) s
	its at the core of any RNA virus replisome and has been a key target for a
	ntiviral development and viral classification. However\, the enzyme is kno
	wn to work in multimeric complexes to achieve different reactions\, reacti
	on controls\, and downstream RNA processing. Many of these complexes remai
	n poorly understood due to insufficient biochemical characterization and l
	ack of solved structures. The crucial RNA capping process is very diverse 
	but remain unevenly understood. Recent advancement of atomic-resolution cr
	yo-EM provided a method to solve some of these structures. I attempted to 
	solve the structures of two such complexes with this method. One was the p
	oliovirus replication initiation complex\, where the RdRp synthesizes the 
	replication primer by covalently adding uridine nucleotides to a viral pro
	tein\, using the viral protease and an RNA hairpin as cofactors. While the
	 structure could not be solved\, biochemical assays nevertheless showed be
	haviors of the complex that could aid future resolution. The other was an 
	RdRp-capping protein heterodimeric complex from Polymycoviridae\, a relati
	vely newly discovered family of fungal viruses. The structure of the compl
	ex was solved to 3.32 Å resolution. The result would not only improve our 
	understanding of this family of fungal virus but also reveal a new type of
	 RdRp-capping protein organization. Simultaneously\, I also purified and b
	iochemically characterized all four conserved proteins\, one of the first 
	for any fungal viruses. The methods and conclusions should help any future
	 investigations into Polymycoviridae and potentially lead to biocontrol me
	thods against fungal pathogens.  &#160\;  (Department : BioSciences-Bioche
	mistry and Cell Biology)\n\nhttps://events.rice.edu/live/events/431477-bio
	chemical-and-structural-characterization-of\n\nFrom Rice University - Open
	 to the Public
URL:https://events.rice.edu/live/events/431477-biochemical-and-structural-c
	haracterization-of
GEO:29.7174;-95.4018
LOCATION:BioScience Research Collaborative
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:rice-public-events
CATEGORIES:Rice University - Open to the Public
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT1H
END:VEVENT
